HIG-21-020

Measurement of boosted Higgs bosons produced via vector boson fusion or gluon fusion in the \PH‚Üí\bbbar‚Üí\PH\bbbar\PH\to\bbbar‚Üí decay mode using LHC proton-proton collision data at s=13‚Å¢\TeVùë†13\TeV\sqrt{s}=13\TeVsquare-root start_ARG italic_s end_ARG = 13

(July 10, 2024)
Abstract

A measurement is performed of Higgs bosons produced with high transverse momentum (\pt) via vector boson or gluon fusion in proton-proton collisions. The result is based on a data set with a center-of-mass energy of 13\TeVcollected in 2016‚Äì2018 with the CMS detector at the LHC and corresponds to an integrated luminosity of 138\fbinv. The decay of a high-\ptHiggs boson to a boosted bottom quark-antiquark pair is selected using large-radius jets and employing jet substructure and heavy-flavor taggers based on machine learning techniques. Independent regions targeting the vector boson and gluon fusion mechanisms are defined based on the topology of two quark-initiated jets with large pseudorapidity separation. The signal strengths for both processes are extracted simultaneously by performing a maximum likelihood fit to data in the large-radius jet mass distribution. The observed signal strengths relative to the standard model expectation are 4.9‚àí1.6+1.9subscriptsuperscript4.91.91.64.9^{+1.9}_{-1.6}4.9 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT + 1.9 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start_POSTSUBSCRIPT - 1.6 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and 1.6‚àí1.5+1.7subscriptsuperscript1.61.71.51.6^{+1.7}_{-1.5}1.6 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT + 1.7 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start_POSTSUBSCRIPT - 1.5 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT for the vector boson and gluon fusion mechanisms, respectively. A differential cross section measurement is also reported in the simplified template cross section framework.

0.1 Introduction

The observation at the CERN LHC of a Higgs boson (\PH) consistent with the standard model (SM) expectation and the subsequent measurements of its properties¬†[1, 2, 3, 4, 5] have advanced the understanding of electroweak (EW) symmetry breaking and the origin of the mass of fundamental particles¬†[6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13]. Higgs boson production at high momentum transfer can be a sensitive probe of beyond the SM (BSM) physics at high energy scales, and measurements in this regime provide important input for effective field theory interpretations of \PHinteractions¬†[14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19]. Thus, studying Higgs bosons at high transverse momentum (\pt\pt\pt) has become an integral part of the physics program at the LHC.

The Higgs boson decay to a bottom quark-antiquark pair (\bbbar\bbbar\bbbar) has the highest branching fraction of any \PHdecay mode¬†[20]. When the Higgs boson is produced with high momentum, the \PH‚Üí\bbbar‚Üí\PH\bbbar\PH\to\bbbar‚Üí decay products are merged into a single large-radius jet. This distinctive boosted jet topology can be identified by its substructure and heavy flavor properties, and as a result the \PH‚Üí\bbbar‚Üí\PH\bbbar\PH\to\bbbar‚Üí decay provides an important channel for the exploration of Higgs boson production at high \pt\pt\pt.

Leading order (LO) Feynman diagrams of the three \PHproduction mechanisms with highest cross section in proton-proton (\Pp‚Å¢\Pp\Pp\Pp\Pp\Pp) collisions are shown in Fig.¬†1: gluon fusion (ggF), vector boson fusion (VBF), and vector boson associated production (\PV‚Å¢\PH\PV\PH\PV\PH). A small contribution to the \PHcross section also arises from associated production with a top quark-antiquark pair (\ttbar‚Å¢\PH\ttbar\PH\ttbar\PH). The dominant SM contribution comes from ggF, which contributes 87% of the \PHcross section at s=13‚Å¢\TeVùë†13\TeV\sqrt{s}=13\TeVsquare-root start_ARG italic_s end_ARG = 13 when considering the full range of Higgs boson \pt. However, the relative contribution from ggF is expected to decrease with the \ptof the Higgs boson, contributing only 50 (30)% of the cumulative \PHcross section for \pt>450\pt450\pt>450> 450 (1200)\GeV¬†[21]. While the relative contribution from \PV‚Å¢\PH\PV\PH\PV\PH increases as a function of Higgs boson \pt, that of VBF has minimal \ptdependence. Each of these production mechanisms provides a different probe of \PHinteractions, and precise measurement of each one is necessary to investigate all possible manifestations of BSM physics in the Higgs sector.

Existing searches in the boosted \PH‚Üí\bbbar‚Üí\PH\bbbar\PH\to\bbbar‚Üí channel from the ATLAS and CMS experiments have focused on inclusive Higgs boson production¬†[22, 23, 24] or associated production with a vector boson¬†[25, 26, 27]. This work extends, for the first time, high-\pt\pt\pt Higgs boson measurements in the \PH‚Üí\bbbar‚Üí\PH\bbbar\PH\to\bbbar‚Üí channel to VBF production. The analysis is performed using pp collision data collected with the CMS detector at the LHC in 2016‚Äì2018, corresponding to an integrated luminosity of 138\fbinv¬†[28, 29, 30]. The VBF process, which is sensitive to \PHcouplings to vector bosons, and the ggF process, which is primarily sensitive to \PHcouplings to top quarks and gluons, are measured simultaneously. In order to disentangle the two processes, the analysis is performed in two categories. The first category is enriched in VBF events and targets the characteristic topology of two quark-initiated jets with high pseudorapidity (Œ∑ùúÇ\etaitalic_Œ∑). The second category is enriched in ggF events.

In both categories, the \PH‚Üí\bbbar‚Üí\PH\bbbar\PH\to\bbbar‚Üí decay mode is isolated from quark- and gluon-initiated jets by a multivariate large-radius jet classifier known as the DeepDoubleB (DDB) tagger¬†[31]. Updates with respect to the previous version of the DDB tagger¬†[32, 33] yield a gain in expected signal significance of about a factor of 2 compared to the previous CMS \PH‚Üí\bbbar‚Üí\PH\bbbar\PH\to\bbbar‚Üí search¬†[24]. As a result, the analysis reported here provides not only the first measurement of \PHproduction via VBF at high \pt\pt\pt, but also the most precise measurement of ggF Higgs boson production in this regime, superseding the measurement in Ref.¬†[24].

0.2 The CMS detector

The CMS apparatus¬†[34] is a multipurpose, nearly hermetic detector, designed to trigger on¬†[35, 36] and identify electrons, muons, photons, and hadrons¬†[37, 38, 39]. Information about particles traversing the detector is provided by the all-silicon inner tracker, and by the crystal electromagnetic and brass-scintillator hadron calorimeters, all of which operate inside a 3.8\unitT superconducting solenoid, and by the gas-ionization muon detectors embedded in the flux-return yoke outside the solenoid.

Events of interest are selected using a two-tiered trigger system. The first level, composed of custom hardware processors, uses information from the calorimeters and muon detectors to select events at a rate of around 100\unitkHz within a fixed latency of about 4\mus¬†[35]. The second level, known as the high-level trigger, consists of a farm of processors running a version of the full event reconstruction software optimized for fast processing, and reduces the event rate to around 1\unitkHz before data storage¬†[36].

A more detailed description of the CMS detector, together with a definition of the coordinate system used and the relevant kinematic variables, can be found in Ref.¬†[34].

The dataset used in this analysis is divided into four data-taking periods to account for the 2017 upgrade of the CMS tracking detector, differences in accelerator and detector conditions, and updates to reconstruction algorithms and calibrations. These data-taking periods correspond to early 2016, late 2016, 2017, and 2018. Data from 2016 is split into an early and a late data-taking period due to changes made mid-year.

0.3 Simulated samples

Simulated samples of signal and background events are produced using various Monte Carlo (MC) event generators, with the CMS detector response modeled by \GEANTfour¬†[40]. Independent samples are generated for each of the four data-taking periods using identical generator configurations, but accounting for changes in the accelerator and detector running conditions.

The background from jets produced via the strong interaction, referred to as quantum chromodynamics (QCD) multijet events, is modeled at LO accuracy using the \MGvATNLO¬†2.4.2 generator¬†[41] with up to four partons from the matrix element calculation.

The \PW\PW\PW+jets and \PZ\PZ\PZ+jets processes are modeled at LO accuracy using the \MGvATNLOgenerator. These samples include decays of the bosons to all flavors of quarks and up to three (four) extra partons at the matrix element level for \PW\PW\PW+jets (\PZ\PZ\PZ+jets). Jets from the matrix element calculations and parton shower description are matched using the MLM prescription¬†[42]. Correction factors are applied to the \PW\PW\PW+jets and \PZ\PZ\PZ+jets samples to match the generator-level \ptdistributions with those predicted by the highest available order in the perturbative expansion. The QCD next-to-LO (NLO) corrections are derived using \MGvATNLO, simulating \PWand \PZboson production with up to two additional partons and FxFx matching to the parton shower¬†[43]. The EW NLO corrections are taken from theoretical calculations in Refs¬†[44, 45, 46, 47].

Electroweak production of \PW\PW\PW and \PZ\PZ\PZ bosons is modeled using \MGvATNLOat LO accuracy. Diboson processes are modeled at LO accuracy with \PYTHIA¬†8.226¬†[48], and the total cross sections are corrected to next-to-NLO (NNLO) accuracy with the \MCFM¬†7.0 program¬†[49]. Top quark-antiquark (\ttbar) and single-top quark production are modeled at NLO in QCD using \POWHEG¬†2.0¬†[50, 51, 52, 53, 54].

The ggF Higgs boson production process is simulated using the HJMINLO event generator¬†[55, 56] with the Higgs boson mass set to 125‚Å¢\GeV125\GeV125\GeV125. Finite top quark mass effects¬†[57] are included following the recommendation in Ref.¬†[21]. The \POWHEGgenerator¬†[58, 59, 60] is used to model Higgs boson production via VBF, \PV‚Å¢\PH\PV\PH\PV\PH, and \ttbar‚Å¢\PH\ttbar\PH\ttbar\PH at NLO accuracy. The VBF sample is reweighted to account for NNLO corrections to the \pt\pt\pt spectrum and N3LO corrections to the inclusive cross section¬†[61, 62]. These corrections have a negligible effect on the yield for this process for events with Higgs boson \pt>450‚Å¢\GeV\pt450\GeV\pt>450\GeV> 450. EW corrections are also applied to the VBF, \PV‚Å¢\PH\PV\PH\PV\PH, and \ttbar‚Å¢\PH\ttbar\PH\ttbar\PH processes¬†[21].

For parton showering and hadronization, all generated samples are interfaced with \PYTHIA¬†8.230, with the parameters for the underlying event description set via the CP5 tune¬†[63]. The parton distribution function (PDF) set NNPDF3.1¬†[64] at NNLO accuracy is used for all processes.

0.4 Event reconstruction and selection

The particle-flow (PF) algorithm¬†[65] aims to reconstruct and identify each individual particle in an event using an optimized combination of information from the various elements of the CMS detector. The primary vertex is taken to be the vertex corresponding to the hardest scattering in the event, evaluated using tracking information alone, as described in Ref.¬†[39].

Jets are reconstructed by clustering PF candidates using the anti-\ktalgorithm¬†[66] as implemented in the \FASTJETsoftware package¬†[67]. Small-radius jets are clustered with a distance parameter of 0.4. Large-radius jets, which are used to capture the decay products of heavy boosted objects, use a distance parameter of 0.8¬†[68].

Jet momentum is taken to be the vectorial sum of all PF candidate momenta in the jet. Additional pp interactions within the same or nearby bunch crossings, known as pileup, can increase the apparent jet momentum by contributing additional tracks and calorimetric energy deposits. To mitigate this effect for small-radius jets, tracks originating from pileup vertices are discarded and an offset correction is applied to correct for remaining contributions¬†[69]. For large-radius jets, the pileup per particle identification algorithm¬†[70] is used to weight the PF candidates prior to jet clustering. Jet energy corrections are derived from simulation to bring the measured response of jets to that of particle level jets on average¬†[71]. Additional selection criteria are applied to remove jets that are likely to be dominated by instrumental effects or reconstruction failures¬†[69, 68].

To isolate the \PHsignal, a large-radius jet with high \ptis required. Events are selected by a combination of triggers, with each trigger imposing a minimum threshold on either the \pt\pt\pt of a large-radius jet or the event \HT\HT\HT, the scalar \pt\pt\pt sum of all small-radius jets in the event with \abs‚Å¢Œ∑<3\absùúÇ3\abs{\eta}<3italic_Œ∑ < 3. For large-radius jets used in the trigger selection, a minimum trimmed jet mass¬†[72] is also required. The VBF category is divided into two bins in mjjsubscriptùëöjjm_{\text{jj}}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT jj end_POSTSUBSCRIPT with different signal purity: 1<mjj<2‚Å¢\TeV1subscriptùëöjj2\TeV1<m_{\text{jj}}<2\TeV1 < italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT jj end_POSTSUBSCRIPT < 2 and mjj>2‚Å¢\TeVsubscriptùëöjj2\TeVm_{\text{jj}}>2\TeVitalic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT jj end_POSTSUBSCRIPT > 2. When combined statistically, this yields about 20% improvement in the significance of a VBF signal compared to a single bin. Similarly, the ggF category is divided into six bins in the \PHcandidate jet \pt\pt\pt with boundaries 450, 500, 550, 600, 675, 800, and 1200\GeV. The upper \ptbound of 1200\GeVdoes not have a significant impact on the sensitivity and excludes a region where the QCD multijet background is difficult to model. The subdivision into \pt\pt\pt bins improves the expected ggF significance by about 20%.

0.5 Background estimation

Because of its large cross section, QCD multijet production is the dominant background in the combined DDB pass and fail regions. Significant resonant backgrounds arise from \PW\PW\PW+jets and \PZ\PZ\PZ+jets processes, where the two-prong decay of a high-\pt\pt\pt vector boson is mistagged as a \PHcandidate. Electroweak \PWand \PZboson production contribute in particular to the background in the VBF category because of the presence of two forward quark-initiated jets. For events in which a high-\pt\pt\pt top quark is produced, it is possible that a large-radius jet captures only two of the three prongs of the decay and passes the N21,DDTsuperscriptsubscriptùëÅ21DDTN_{2}^{1,\text{DDT}}italic_N start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 1 , DDT end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT selection. The presence of a bottom quark in these decays makes them more likely to pass the DDB requirement. In this way, top quark production contributes to the nonresonant component of the background. This section describes the estimate of the background contribution from each of these processes.

Additional small background contributions from diboson, \PV‚Å¢\PH\PV\PH\PV\PH, and \ttbar‚Å¢\PH\ttbar\PH\ttbar\PH processes (each expected to be <1%absentpercent1<1\%< 1 % of the total background) are estimated from simulation. Both \PV‚Å¢\PH\PV\PH\PV\PH and \ttbar‚Å¢\PH\ttbar\PH\ttbar\PH are assumed to occur at SM rates.

0.5.3 Top quark background

Top quark processes contribute a nonresonant component of a few percent to the total background. While the shape of the mSDsubscriptùëöSDm_{\mathrm{SD}}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT roman_SD end_POSTSUBSCRIPT distributions in \ttbar\ttbar\ttbar and single-top quark processes are estimated from simulation, both the overall normalization and the DDB tagger efficiency are constrained using data. 0.6 Systematic uncertainties

Several sources of experimental uncertainty arise from the reconstruction and calibration of physics objects from low-level detector responses.

A data-to-simulation scale factor is applied to the \PH‚Üí\bbbar‚Üí\PH\bbbar\PH\to\bbbar‚Üí and \PZ‚Üí\bbbar‚Üí\PZ\bbbar\PZ\to\bbbar‚Üí predictions to account for the difference in efficiency of the DDB tagger selection. This scale factor is included in the signal extraction fit as a constrained nuisance parameter with a nominal value of unity and a conservative uncertainty of 30%. The magnitude of this uncertainty is based on the results of dedicated measurements in QCD multijet events with gluon to \bbbar\bbbar\bbbar splitting topologies similar to the \PH‚Üí\bbbar‚Üí\PH\bbbar\PH\to\bbbar‚Üí signal¬†[85], but a precise scale factor cannot be derived due to the limited number of gluon splitting events in the \ptregime relevant for this analysis. The DDB scale factor is instead constrained in situ via the observed \PZ‚Üí\bbbar‚Üí\PZ\bbbar\PZ\to\bbbar‚Üí yield in the DDB pass and fail regions and constitutes the dominant experimental uncertainty.

The uncertainties on the corrections for substructure selection, jet mass scale, and jet mass resolution detailed in Section¬†0.5.2 are treated as constrained nuisance parameters. These uncertainties are correlated among the \PW, \PZ, and Higgs boson production processes, and are further constrained by the presence of \PWand \PZboson resonances in the mSDsubscriptùëöSDm_{\mathrm{SD}}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT roman_SD end_POSTSUBSCRIPT distribution. Additional systematic uncertainties are applied to the event yields of \PW\PW\PW+jets, \PZ\PZ\PZ+jets, \ttbar\ttbar\ttbar, and Higgs boson production to account for the uncertainties due to the jet energy scale and resolution¬†[71, 86] and the limited event count of simulated samples. A bin-by-bin uncertainty is applied to account for the limited number of simulated QCD events in the dedicated fit to determine the transfer factor TP/FsubscriptùëáP/FT_{\text{P/F}}italic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT P/F end_POSTSUBSCRIPT .

Other experimental uncertainties, including those related to the determination of the integrated luminosity¬†[28, 29, 30], variations in the amount of pileup obtained by adjusting the total inelastic cross section, modeling of the trigger efficiency, and the isolation and identification of the veto leptons are also considered, and contribute only a few percent to the total uncertainty.

In addition to experimental uncertainties, theoretical uncertainties are included in the final fit to account for inaccuracy in the modeling of SM processes.

The dominant theoretical uncertainty applied to all Higgs boson signal processes is due to the choice of renormalization and factorization scales. This uncertainty is propagated to the total expected yield of the \PHsignal according to the prescription recommended in Ref.¬†[21], amounting to approximately 20% and 5% in the ggF and VBF signal yields, respectively. Uncertainties in the \PHsignal yields due to initial- and final-state radiation are also calculated by varying the renormalization scale and non-singular term using the \PYTHIA¬†8 showering algorithm¬†[87]. The Hessian PDF uncertainty is also applied to \PHsignal yield, according to the prescription of Ref.¬†[88].

Theoretical uncertainties on the \PW\PW\PW+jets and \PZ\PZ\PZ+jets processes account for missing higher-order QCD and mixed QCD-EW effects beyond the corrections described in Section¬†0.3, following the prescription of Ref.¬†[47].

All theoretical uncertainties are considered to be correlated across all data-taking periods, and experimental systematic uncertainties are considered to be uncorrelated, with the exception of a correlated component of the uncertainty on the integrated luminosity (‚Ñí‚Ñí\mathcal{L}caligraphic_L). All systematic uncertainties are incorporated into the analysis via nuisance parameters and treated according to the frequentist paradigm¬†[89].

Among the largest sources of systematic uncertainty are the theoretical uncertainties in the Higgs boson production cross section, the size of simulated signal samples, and the uncertainty in the data-to-simulation scale factor on the DDB tagger selection. Overall, the measurement is limited by the statistical uncertainty in data, including the limited sample size available to determine the QCD background yield under the Higgs boson peak via the transfer factor TressubscriptùëáresT_{\text{res}}italic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT res end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, as discussed in Section¬†0.5.1.

0.7 Results

A binned maximum likelihood fit to the observed mSDsubscriptùëöSDm_{\mathrm{SD}}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT roman_SD end_POSTSUBSCRIPT distributions is performed using the sum of the signal and background contributions. The test statistic chosen to determine the signal yield is based on the profile likelihood ratio¬†[89]. The fit is performed simultaneously in many bins: in both mjjsubscriptùëöjjm_{\text{jj}}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT jj end_POSTSUBSCRIPT bins of the VBF category and all \pt\pt\pt bins of ggF category, in the single-muon control region, in both the DDB pass and fail regions, and in all four data-taking periods. The observed data and post-fit mSDsubscriptùëöSDm_{\mathrm{SD}}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT roman_SD end_POSTSUBSCRIPT distributions in the VBF category are shown in Fig.¬†4. For display purposes, the data and fitted distributions in this Figure are summed over both mjjsubscriptùëöjjm_{\text{jj}}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT jj end_POSTSUBSCRIPT bins and all four data-taking periods. For the ggF category, the observed data and post-fit mSDsubscriptùëöSDm_{\mathrm{SD}}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT roman_SD end_POSTSUBSCRIPT distributions are shown in Fig.¬†5, again summed over all six \pt\pt\pt bins and all data-taking periods for display purposes. The data and post-fit event yields in the single-muon CR are shown for each data-taking period in Table¬†0.7.

The best fit value of the signal strength, defined as the ratio of the measured to the SM expected cross section times \PH‚Üí\bbbar‚Üí\PH\bbbar\PH\to\bbbar‚Üí branching fraction, and an approximate 68% confidence level (CL) interval are extracted following Ref.¬†[90]. The fitted signal strengths for VBF and ggF \PHproduction, denoted ŒºVBFsubscriptùúáVBF\mu_{\text{VBF}}italic_Œº start_POSTSUBSCRIPT VBF end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and ŒºggFsubscriptùúággF\mu_{\text{ggF}}italic_Œº start_POSTSUBSCRIPT ggF end_POSTSUBSCRIPT respectively, are extracted separately for the four data-taking periods, and a combined fit over the full data set is performed for the final result. The \PV‚Å¢\PH\PV\PH\PV\PH and \ttbar‚Å¢\PH\ttbar\PH\ttbar\PH processes are assumed to occur at SM rates. The results are summarized in Table¬†0.7. The combined signal strength for the VBF process is measured to be 4.9‚àí1.6+1.9subscriptsuperscript4.91.91.64.9^{+1.9}_{-1.6}4.9 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT + 1.9 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start_POSTSUBSCRIPT - 1.6 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, and the combined signal strength for the ggF process is measured to be 1.6‚àí1.5+1.7subscriptsuperscript1.61.71.51.6^{+1.7}_{-1.5}1.6 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT + 1.7 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start_POSTSUBSCRIPT - 1.5 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. Tabulated results are provided in the HEPData record for this analysis¬†[91].

Figure¬†6 shows the combined two-dimensional likelihood scan performed over the VBF and ggF signal strengths. The best fit point differs from the SM expectation by 2.7‚ÄâœÉùúé\sigmaitalic_œÉ, and from the null hypothesis (no \PHproduction) by 4.0‚ÄâœÉùúé\sigmaitalic_œÉ.

0.7.1 Differential measurement

The observed mSDsubscriptùëöSDm_{\mathrm{SD}}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT roman_SD end_POSTSUBSCRIPT distributions in the DDB pass region are shown separately in each bin in Figs.¬†7 and¬†8, for VBF and ggF, respectively. The signal strength is also fitted independently per reconstruction-level bin. Because the VBF (ggF) category can only weakly constrain the ggF (VBF) process, the ratio of ggF to VBF is fixed to the SM expectation in this fit. The results are shown in Fig.¬†9.

A maximum likelihood unfolding technique¬†[92] is used to remove the effects of limited detector acceptance and response on the measured production cross section. The fiducial cross section is extracted simultaneously in five bins, each of which is considered as a separate process and modified by a freely floating signal strength parameter in the likelihood model. The three bins in the ggF channel correspond to generated Higgs boson \ptin the ranges 300‚Äì450, 450‚Äì650, and >650‚Å¢\GeVabsent650\GeV>650\GeV> 650. The two bins in the VBF channel correspond to \pt\PH>200‚Å¢\GeVsuperscript\pt\PH200\GeV\pt^{\PH}>200\GeVstart_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT > 200 and mjjgensuperscriptsubscriptùëöjjgenm_{\text{jj}}^{\text{gen}}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT jj end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT gen end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT in the ranges 1000‚Äì1500\GeVand >1500‚Å¢\GeVabsent1500\GeV>1500\GeV> 1500, where mjjgensuperscriptsubscriptùëöjjgenm_{\text{jj}}^{\text{gen}}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT jj end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT gen end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT is the generator-level invariant mass of the forward quark-initiated jets. This choice of bins is consistent with the simplified template cross section (STXS) stage 1.2 scheme ¬†[93, 20]. Additional STXS bins corresponding to ggF with \pt\PH<300‚Å¢\GeVsuperscript\pt\PH300\GeV\pt^{\PH}<300\GeVstart_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT < 300 and VBF with \pt\PH<200‚Å¢\GeVsuperscript\pt\PH200\GeV\pt^{\PH}<200\GeVstart_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT < 200 or mjjgen<1000‚Å¢\GeVsuperscriptsubscriptùëöjjgen1000\GeVm_{\text{jj}}^{\text{gen}}<1000\GeVitalic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT jj end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT gen end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT < 1000 are found to have negligible contribution to the signal region. The \PHsignal yields in these bins are assumed to occur at SM rates.

For the theoretical uncertainties, only those that affect the acceptance of signal events into the analysis selection are taken into account. Each fitted signal strength parameter and its uncertainty are scaled by the corresponding simulated cross section to obtain the best fit estimator for the cross section and its uncertainty.

The unfolded fiducial cross sections are shown in Fig.¬†10, with the predictions from the signal event generators overlaid. The measured cross sections and uncertainties are also reported in Table¬†0.7.1. The best fit for the ggF bin with 300<\pt\PH<450‚Å¢\GeV300superscript\pt\PH450\GeV300<\pt^{\PH}<450\GeV300 < start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT < 450 lies below zero cross section, as can happen when the signal is estimated with a fit over a large background. However, the uncertainty in this bin is found to be comparatively large due to the limited number of these events passing the analysis selection, and the SM cross section value is well within the uncertainty.

0.8 Summary

A measurement has been performed of boosted Higgs bosons (\PH) produced via vector boson fusion (VBF) or gluon fusion (ggF) and decaying to bottom quark-antiquark pairs. The analysis goes beyond the inclusive \PH‚Üí\bbbar‚Üí\PH\bbbar\PH\to\bbbar‚Üí measurements performed thus far to provide the first exploration of Higgs bosons produced with high transverse momentum (\pt>450‚Å¢\GeV\pt450\GeV\pt>450\GeV> 450) in the VBF channel. The signal strengths for both processes are extracted simultaneously by performing a maximum likelihood fit to data in the large-radius jet mass distribution. The observed signal strengths for the VBF and ggF processes are 4.9‚àí1.6+1.9subscriptsuperscript4.91.91.64.9^{+1.9}_{-1.6}4.9 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT + 1.9 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start_POSTSUBSCRIPT - 1.6 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and 1.6‚àí1.5+1.7subscriptsuperscript1.61.71.51.6^{+1.7}_{-1.5}1.6 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT + 1.7 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start_POSTSUBSCRIPT - 1.5 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, corresponding to a 2.7‚ÄâœÉùúé\sigmaitalic_œÉ difference between data and the standard model expectation. The unfolded simplified template cross sections, which will provide an important input to future combined interpretations of \PHinteractions, are also reported.
